  "texts": [
    "Loewe Additivity, defined by Loewe in 1926, is based on the principle of sham combination which assumes no interaction effect when a compound is combined with itself (Loewe, 1953).",
    "It is a dose-effect-based concept that is widely used in pharmacology and toxicology.",
    "In pharmacology, a dose-response curve is a graphical representation of the relationship between the dose of a drug or compound and its effect.",
    "The curve shows how the effect changes as the dose increases.",
    "Loewe additivity assumes that the dose-response curves for two compounds are parallel, meaning that they have the same shape and slope."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Loewe Additivity, defined by Loewe in 1926, is based on the principle of sham combination which assumes no interaction effect when a compound is combined with itself (Loewe, 1953)."
